<h4 id="using-checkbox">Using checkbox</h4>

<p>Checkbox enables users to select more than one choice at a time from a selection of inputs, for examples all items that apply from a list.</p>

<p>If you want users to select just one input at a time, for examples a yes or no answer, use the <a href="radio">radio element</a></p>

<p>Checkbox is often used as part of a <a href="form">form</a>.</p>

<p>You can avoid having long lists of options by guiding users through with better thought out questions.</p>

<p>Conditionality allows you to show users additional content or questions to particular users on what they’ve selected. If you’re using this to show lots of content, maybe think about putting it on a separate page.</p>

<h3 id="content-break">Content break</h3>

<div class="content-break-large"></div>

<div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>&lt;div class="content-break-large"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
</code></pre></div></div>

<div class="content-break-small"></div>

<div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>&lt;div class="content-break-small"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
</code></pre></div></div>

<h4 id="using-content-breaks">Using content breaks</h4>

<p>Content breaks are visual elements used to separate sections of content.</p>

<p>They should be used to:</p>
<ul>
  <li>thematically divide up sections of content, such as services, news and legislation</li>
  <li>show a divide between a list of clickable items, such as news articles, service links or guidance documents</li>
</ul>

<p>They shouldn’t be used to divide paragraphs within the body of content.</p>

<h3 id="dropdown">Dropdown</h3>

<div class="form">
  <div class="group">
    <label for="sorting" class="form-hint">Sort by</label>
    <select class="form-control" id="sorting" name="sorting">
      <option>Recently published</option>
      <option selected="">Recently updated</option>
      <option>Most views</option>
      <option>Most comments</option>
    </select>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>&lt;div class="form"&gt;
  &lt;div class="group"&gt;
    &lt;label for="sorting" class="form-hint"&gt;Sort by&lt;/label&gt;
    &lt;select class="form-control" id="sorting" name="sorting"&gt;
      &lt;option&gt;Recently published&lt;/option&gt;
      &lt;option selected&gt;Recently updated&lt;/option&gt;
      &lt;option&gt;Most views&lt;/option&gt;
      &lt;option&gt;Most comments&lt;/option&gt;
    &lt;/select&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
</code></pre></div></div>

<h4 id="using-dropdown">Using dropdown</h4>

<p>Dropdown should only be used if there is no other alternative as some users can struggle with the functionality.</p>

<p>Try using the <a href="radio">radio</a> or <a href="checkbox">checkbox</a> elements instead.</p>

<p>It’s often used when there is a long list that can’t presented in another way, such as a list of countries or languages.</p>

<p><em>Note: Be sure to update all label and input attributes with the correct details i.e.</em></p>

<div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>&lt;label for=""&gt;&lt;/label&gt;
&lt;select id=""&gt;
&lt;select naming=""&gt;
</code></pre></div></div>

